attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, Intel 80386, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, for GNU/Linux 2.6.9, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a malicious backdoor, likely a variant of the BillGates/XOR.DDoS malware family. It establishes persistence by creating init.d scripts (`/etc/init.d/%s`, `/etc/rc%d.d/S90%s`) and a cron job (`/etc/cron.hourly/gcc.sh`, `sed -i '/.../d' /etc/crontab`). It performs network communication via HTTP GET/POST requests, likely to a command and control server. The malware also employs anti-forensics by disabling the MySQL history file (`MYSQL_HISTFILE=/dev/null`) and information gathering by reading `/proc/net/tcp`, `/proc/cpuinfo`, and `/proc/meminfo`.
